[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Java Modules**\n\nI'm thinking about whether a Java named module can read unnamed modules. The general rule is that named modules do not read unnamed ones. But wait, could canRead return true for unnamed modules? I'm considering running a small Java test, but the instructions say not to compile or run tests myself, which makes it tricky. I could try using code introspection instead. Maybe the previous issue happened because both modules shared the same classloader?\n\n**Evaluating test structure**\n\nIŌĆÖm considering splitting the test class into separate files to have a one-to-one mapping with the dynamic-access class. Keeping tests within the same class makes sense, allowing for flexibility in order. I could also simplify by removing direct references to ClassReloadingStrategy.fromInstalledAgent since itŌĆÖs already covered. I wonder whether I need to set up two modules for loading classes and an agent installer, especially if they share packages.\n\n**Reasoning about class loading**\n\nI'm analyzing how the BuiltinClassLoader functions, particularly focusing on the map `nameToModule` for modules defined within it. I think `loadClassOrNull(cn)` might search for loaded classes, parent classes, and then possibly look for them on the classpath. For named modules, it appears that `loadClass(Module, name)` would work, while the generic version may not search all named modules. I believe it's important to ensure the module's structure aligns and I need the `module-info` for the agent module.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_080a077674b6d198016a29476d86a481909f264de6a2acc90c\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKUei_QQv0Ax7Cfum02hty0DSMVcBtO6hpd-h8H0igNwnq-4EOYU-gvbSyplYKT5UyWgFdtRVcSPH7zD3kJmAd8Q8Cfgs22YUzSR_i4suyQxl1dsb6vk12301_1Cly12oSydCT8yglYC7xrJnaJ5dpEWWmlLeJY0j6imsSeFhnuUuq--JMk2f16TkPC54PJIaNVQRB9Qzw66qw